<p class="project-subheading">What is the pantosphere?<br /></p>
<div class="project-paragraph">
    The Pantosphere's form is an inverted sphere. The surface is comprised of static artefacts of the old epoch, the Anthropocene, and the new epochs artfacts; the rapid accumulation of digital data build up.
    
    The Pantoscene is a digital epoch that is volitile and unpredictable between an instant to a second. Every click and scroll and end history browsing data is accumulating and forming a new geological layer.
    <br /><br />


  </div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-6 d-flex align-items-center">
      
        <div class="project-paragraph">
          
            
          <br />

            When we are sleeping, our digital persona synchronously obtains and distributes personal fragments of ourselves and others. We‚Äôre helpless to stop it. The Pantosphere spacializes the blind forfeiture of our intimate selves to artificial intelligence. Website cookies, IP footprints, retargeting tactics, and the statistical self, exposes our personal vulnerability to an artificial omniscient.
            
            The aesthetic qualities of the Pantosphere are insprired by popular instagram visual artists such as <a class="link" href="https://www.instagram.com/klarens/?hl=en">@klarenns</a>. The vibrancy of colour and selective lighting highlights the stark, staticness of the old artfact of a previous era.
        </div>
            
           
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-6 d-flex align-items-center">
        <div class="img-container-1">
            <img class="img-container-1" src="/assets/images/pantosphere/binary.png" alt="Single consult room" />
            <figcaption class="caption">Binary code, translating to the names of four Pantopes (group members): Isabel Caleb Brett Beverly, the Pantoscene layer.</figcaption>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<p><br /><br />
<br /></p>
<p class="project-subheading">Producing the Pantosphere<br /></p>
<div class="project-paragraph">
    The pantosphere base "OG" surface is a mere 200m radius primitive sphere component that was baked and re-referenced into grasshopper . The "references" were about 60 totum threads categorised into groups of 3 (short, medium and long threads). The three categories of threads were baked into individual 'slices' at varying offset lengths (75, 100, 150), to create variation in thread extrusion distances without distorting the threads and their objects. 
    <br /><br />
    In batches, I referenced in these threads, randomised them, and used text tags quickly check that all threads had been referenced, and enough 'randomness' was generated. Without jittering the list of threads, deliberate looking patterns were arising in the slices. Initially the idea was to then randomise the different threads of different heights, however it was decided that the accidental 'portal' like effect created by the longest threads was desirable and dynamic.
    <br /><br />


  </div>

<p><!--next part--></p>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-6 d-flex align-items-center">
        <div>
            <img class="d-block w-100" src="/assets/images/pantosphere/sphere_crop.png" alt="Single consult room" />
            
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-6 d-flex align-items-center">
        <div class="project-paragraph">
            

           
            <br /><br />
            This is not the most complex script I have ever written, but it is one I was able to quickly develop and implement successfully. It is written to minimise the risk of the software crashing and enables a swift, iterative work-flow. With our Grasshopper base model, we went on to use Unreal Engine to construct the Pantosphere and add materials, lighting, and binary code layers, as well as enact a storyboarded experience for the user.
        </div>
        
    </div>
</div>
<p><br /> <br /></p>
<p class="project-subheading">Experience the Pantosphere<br /></p>
<div class="project-paragraph">
    
    The Pantosphere is not meant to feel welcoming and warm but rather hostile, scary and claustrophobic with a impending sense of doom. The user is to experience a world of wonder, that they can only view through spotlights.
    <br /> <br />
    They are otherwise in the dark and must frantically look around to open their field of vision. Glitchy, techy, unnatural sounds surround you. The static artefacts seem to be moving, the sphere as a whole is seemingly spinning on an axis - orbiting. 
    <br /> <br />
    Numbers unnaturally build up, appearing and disappearing, unpredictable? Or following the movement and vision of the user? It appears to be amassing weight each time. But before you an fixate yourself on a artefact as a visual depth cue, you notice that they seem to be closing in on you - at the centre.
    <br /> <br />
    The longest threads hit you first - they go through you and impale you but somehow you escape into the artefacts; you are propelled into the anthropocene layers to the outside of the sphere. 
    <br /> <br />
    It pauses - ...what the?... but now, you hurtle towards the sphere one again, burst through the layers and you gaze upon a portal of artefacts. The sphere grows, or you shrink, and the Pantosphere remains ever-changing, somehow unreachable and unsettling.

    ‚Äã
    <br /> <br />
    Experience it yourself with this recording:
    

