<p class="project-subheading">Reflection<br /></p>
<div class="project-paragraph">
    
    <br />
    I've always struggling with understanding what it is that I like to do in design, and what kind of design work I want to be involved in the future. At the very least I have only known that I feel passionate about some ‚Äòthing‚Äô other than a traditional architecture practice. 
    <br /><br />
 

Initially, I came into the Digital Knitting unit feeling skeptical. Unlike other units we were not workshopping specific software and technical skills, nor did we have a solid brief and outcome in mind. What were we doing? What was the point of this? The idea of the Pantope and Pantopia seemed at first strange and I struggled to allow myself to get into the mindset where I could just ‚Äòroll with it‚Äô. It has been so engrained into me in most studios to ground all my work, theory and ideas in digestible and communicable spaces that are clearly architectural, and I was struggling to do this with such, imaginary(?) ideas. In regular studios I always feel as though im battling to come ot the 'correct' understanding or interpretation of something (ie a brief, my tutors personal prefrences, etc). But I think once I embraced that approach of just thinking about truly speculative ideas, as long as you can back it up, what we were doing started to make more sense and paradoxically my individual and our collective work felt loftier.

‚Äã

After AAVS, I feel enlightened and liberated as a designer. I feel immensely fulfilled with the work I produced, the friends I made, and the maturation of myself as a architecturally trained design-person [placeholder title until I figure out more stuff].
</div>
